If you have on-the-fly pathfinding, is there any utility to defining fixed paths for auto?

I have been thinking about this, and cannot find a good reason. If there would be a lack of accuracy, that just means that the vision and odometry are not accurate, which while certainly a problem, should be fixed anyway to be of any use. If there is concern about predictable pathing and ensuring that it does not get in anyone else’s way, it should move the same path given the same parameters.

Is there anything I am missing here? Obviously you would want to retain final approach paths for consistency, but there seems to be no need for auto specific paths.

The part you are missing is the actual generation of path. In theory, there are paths that exist that are faster than the ones typically used for on-the-fly, but they computationally take so much time to compute that they wouldn’t be useful for on the fly. Since you can precompute paths before autos, there is some possible advantage to be gained. I believe Choreo is like that.

On the optimization and odometry side… there’s a lot of overlap when you get to the upper limits of frc coding.

On the practical side, writing a single “auto script” that can be easily tested and works reliably tends to be much simpler for many teams than a completely event driven automaton with full robot and play field state information. PathPlanner and choreo make correlating path and actions really streamlined, and rely on this level of defined predictability.
